Variability in rainfall can have important consequences for the transmission of rodent-borne diseases (
 Bi et al. 2002; 
 Engelthaler et al. 1999; 
 Ernest et al. 2000; 
 Hjelle and Glass 2000; 
 Madsen and Shine 1999; 
 Nakazawa et al. 2007; 
 Stenseth et al. 2006; 
 Yan et al. 2007) by increasing the growth of vegetation that either directly or indirectly serves as food for rodent hosts, resulting in larger rodent populations. Increased rodent densities can be associated with increased viral transmission among rodent populations and larger numbers of dispersing animals, which in turn lead to increased transmission to humans who contact these animals (
 Engelthaler et al. 1999; 
 Glass et al. 2000, 
 2007; 
 Yates 2002). About 90% of the HFRS epidemic foci in China are in low-lying regions with moist or semimoist soils (
 Bi et al. 2002; 
 Yan et al. 2007). This study corroborates previous findings that rainfall is an important factor in the transmission of HFRS in China.
